</style>


<header>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">Affordable Forever</div>
    <h1>How old will you be when your home <span>expires</span>?</h1>
    <p>
      LIHTC affordability in New York lasts thirty years. The people who move in
      do not stop needing a home after thirty years. Do the arithmetic.
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="container">
  <div class="panel">
    <div class="grid">
      <div>
        <label for="moved">Year you moved in</label>
        <input id="moved" type="number" placeholder="1994" min="1987" max="2026">
      </div>
      <div>
        <label for="age">Your age then</label>
        <input id="age" type="number" placeholder="23" min="0" max="100">
      </div>
      <div>
        <label for="exp">Year it expires</label>
        <input id="exp" type="number" placeholder="2025" min="1990" max="2070">
        <div class="hint">Don't know? Leave blank — we'll assume 30 years.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <button class="go" id="go">Show me</button>

    <div class="answer" id="answer">
      <div class="verdict" id="verdict">
        <div class="lead" id="lead"></div>
        <div class="big" id="big"></div>
        <div class="tail" id="tail"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="facts" id="facts"></div>

      <div class="kicker" id="kicker"></div>

      <div id="qc" style="margin-top:14px;background:#fff;border:1px solid #fecaca;border-left:5px solid var(--red);border-radius:18px;padding:24px 26px">
        <div style="font-size:11px;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#991b1b">There may be an earlier date</div>
        <h3 style="font-size:21px;color:#7f1d1d;margin-top:8px;line-height:1.3">And nobody told you about that one either.</h3>
        <p style="margin-top:12px;font-size:16px;line-height:1.75;color:#450a0a">
          Federal law lets an owner apply to leave the programme after just <strong>fifteen
          years</strong> — the <em>qualified contract</em> loophole. The state gets one year to find
          a buyer who will keep it affordable. If it can't, the affordability period
          <strong>terminates early</strong>.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px;font-size:16px;line-height:1.75;color:#450a0a">
          For your building, fifteen years would have been <strong id="qc-year">—</strong>,
          and you would have been <strong id="qc-age">—</strong>.
        </p>

        <div style="margin-top:16px;padding-top:14px;border-top:1px solid #fecaca">
          <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;color:#450a0a">
            <strong>Does it apply to you? Probably not — but you have to check.</strong>
            New York's allocation plans now <em>require</em> owners to sign away the qualified
            contract right as a condition of receiving credits. But that requirement came in later,
            and <strong>buildings financed before it may still hold that right.</strong> The state's
            own guidance tells owners to go and read their regulatory agreement to find out.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;color:#450a0a;margin-top:10px">
            So ask HCR, in writing: <em>did the owner of my building waive the qualified contract
            right?</em> If your building opened in the 1990s, that is not a rhetorical question.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top:16px;background:#fffbeb;border:1px solid #fde68a;border-radius:12px;padding:16px 18px">
          <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;color:#78350f">
            <strong>And a protection almost nobody knows they have:</strong> if a qualified contract
            does terminate the affordability period early, federal law still requires the owner —
            for <strong>three more years</strong> — to honour the maximum tax-credit rent for
            existing tenants, <em>and to notify you that it happened</em>.
            <br><br>
            If your rent jumped and you were never told about a qualified contract, that is a
            question for a lawyer. Tenants in Missouri are suing over exactly this.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="share">
        <button id="copy">Copy this to share</button>
        <button class="alt" id="again">Try another</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="why">
    <h2>Why this number is the whole argument</h2>
    <p>
      When Congress set the compliance period at thirty years, it was describing a
      <b>financing term</b>. It was not describing a life. Nobody asked the obvious question:
      what happens to the people still living there on the last day?
    </p>
    <p>
      A tenant who moves in at 25 will be 55 when it ends — working, mobile, with options.
      A tenant who moves in at 55 will be <b>85</b>. She will be older, poorer, more likely to be
      disabled, and priced out of the city she spent thirty years in. Same program. Same term.
      Completely different sentence.
    </p>
    <div class="pull">
      The thirty-year term is a bet that tenants won't be there at the end.
      Most of them are.
    </div>
    <p>
      This is why the language matters. The industry calls it a <b>sunset</b>. For the person
      still living in the apartment, it is <b>doomsday</b> — and the difference between those
      two words is the difference between a schedule and a home.
    </p>
    <p>
      States have already fixed this. <b>Vermont</b> requires affordability in perpetuity, and has
      since the early 2000s — and gets two to three times more developer demand than it has credits
      to award. <b>Oregon</b> requires 60 years. <b>California</b>, 55. <b>Massachusetts, Montana
      and Utah</b>, 50. The state average is roughly 42.
    </p>
    <div class="pull">
      New York requires 30. We are below the national average — in the most expensive
      housing market in the country.
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top:20px;font-size:17px">
      <a href="/what-lihtc-is/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">The full argument, and the state-by-state numbers →</a>
    </p>
    <p class="src">
      Sources: National Low Income Housing Coalition; National Housing Trust analysis of state
      Qualified Allocation Plans; Shelterforce. Expiration dates are projections based on a
      30-year term from the year placed in service, not filed dates — see our methodology note.
    </p>
  </section>
</main>



<script>
const $ = id => document.getElementById(id);
const NOW = new Date().getFullYear();
let shareText = "";

function run(){
  const moved = parseInt($('moved').value);
  const ageAt = parseInt($('age').value);
  let   exp   = parseInt($('exp').value);

  if(!moved || isNaN(ageAt)){ alert("Enter the year you moved in and how old you were."); return; }
  if(!exp){ exp = moved + 30; $('exp').value = exp; }

  const ageAtExp = ageAt + (exp - moved);
  const yearsIn  = exp - moved;
  const past     = exp <= NOW;
  const ageNow   = ageAt + (NOW - moved);

  $('verdict').className = 'verdict' + (past ? ' gone' : '');
  $('lead').textContent = past
    ? "Your building's affordability has already expired. When it did, you were"
    : "When your building's affordability expires, you will be";
  $('big').textContent  = ageAtExp;
  $('tail').textContent = past
    ? `years old — after ${yearsIn} years in that home.`
    : `years old — after ${yearsIn} years in that home.`;

  $('facts').innerHTML = `
    <div class="fact"><div class="n">${moved}</div><div class="l">the year you came home</div></div>
    <div class="fact"><div class="n">${yearsIn}</div><div class="l">years of your life in that building</div></div>
    <div class="fact"><div class="n">${exp}</div><div class="l">the year the protection ${past?'ended':'ends'}</div></div>`;

  let k;
  if(ageAtExp >= 75){
    k = `<b>You would be ${ageAtExp}.</b> This is exactly the failure at the heart of the program.
         The people most likely to be living in a building on the day its affordability ends are the
         people least able to absorb it — older, on fixed incomes, more likely to be disabled, and
         priced out of the only city they know. Thirty years was never a policy. It was a financing term.`;
  } else if(ageAtExp >= 60){
    k = `<b>You would be ${ageAtExp}</b> — at or near retirement, on a fixed income, in a market
         where the rent can now go anywhere. A thirty-year clock that starts in middle age ends at
         precisely the worst possible moment.`;
  } else if(ageAtExp >= 45){
    k = `<b>You would be ${ageAtExp}.</b> You'd have spent ${yearsIn} years building a life on that
         block — schools, work, neighbors, a doctor, a route home. None of that is portable, and none
         of it was counted when the term was set.`;
  } else {
    k = `<b>You would be ${ageAtExp}</b> — young enough to start over somewhere else, which is more
         than most of your neighbors can say. Look around your building at the people who moved in the
         same year you did, but twenty years older. Run their number instead.`;
  }
  if(!past && exp > NOW){
    k += `<br><br>That is <b>${exp - NOW} year${exp-NOW===1?'':'s'} from now</b>. You are ${ageNow} today.`;
  }
  $('kicker').innerHTML = k;

  const qcYear = moved + 15;
  const qcAge  = ageAt + 15;
  $('qc-year').textContent = qcYear;
  $('qc-age').textContent  = qcAge + (qcAge === 1 ? ' year old' : ' years old');

  shareText = past
    ? `When my building's affordable housing protections expired in ${exp}, I was ${ageAtExp} years old. I had lived there ${yearsIn} years. LIHTC affordability lasts 30 years — but people don't stop needing a home after 30 years. When they call it a "sunset," for tenants it's doomsday. affordableforever.org`
    : `When my building's affordable housing protections expire in ${exp}, I will be ${ageAtExp} years old. I will have lived there ${yearsIn} years. LIHTC affordability lasts 30 years — but people don't stop needing a home after 30 years. When they call it a "sunset," for tenants it's doomsday. affordableforever.org`;

  $('answer').classList.add('show');
  $('answer').scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth', block:'center'});
}

$('go').addEventListener('click', run);
['moved','age','exp'].forEach(id =>
  $(id).addEventListener('keydown', e => { if(e.key==='Enter') run(); }));

$('copy').addEventListener('click', () => {
  navigator.clipboard.writeText(shareText).then(()=>{
    const b = $('copy'); const t = b.textContent;
    b.textContent = "Copied — go paste it"; setTimeout(()=>b.textContent=t, 2200);
  });
});
$('again').addEventListener('click', () => {
  $('answer').classList.remove('show');
  ['moved','age','exp'].forEach(id => $(id).value='');
  $('moved').focus();
  window.scrollTo({top:0, behavior:'smooth'});
});
</script>
